  "pride_metadata": {
    "project": {
      "accession": "PXD020479",
      "title": "Global Proteomic Analysis of Lysine acetylation in Fusarium oxysporum",
      "additionalAttributes": [],
      "projectDescription": "Lysine  acetylation (Kac), a  discovered post-translational modification, plays a key role in the regulation of diverse cellular processes. Fusarium oxysporumis a destructive necrotrophic fungal pathogen distributed worldwide with broad ranging hosts. However, the functions of Kac are unknown in Fusarium oxysporumr any other plant fungal pathogens. Here, we comprehensively evaluated the acetylation proteome ofFusarium oxysporum .",
      "sampleProcessingProtocol": "Protein Extraction FromFusarium oxysporum  The protein extraction was performed as previously described (Zhou et al., 2016). Briefly, the harvested mycelia were ground into powder in liquid nitrogen. Then the powder sample was suspended by lysis buffer (50 mM nicotinamide, 8 M urea, 65 mM dithiothreitol, 1% Triton-100, 0.1% protease inhibitor cocktail, 2 mM EDTA, and 3 \u03bcM Trichostatin A) and then sonicated. After centrifugation at 15,000 x g in 4\u2103 for 15 min, 15% cold TCA was used to precipitate the proteins at -20\u2103 for 2 h. The precipitates were washed three times with cold acetone after centrifugation at 4\u2103for 15 min. Finally, the target protein was redissolved in 8 M urea supplemented with 100 mM NH4CO3 (PH 8.0) and 2-D Quant kit (GE Healthcare) was used to determine protein concentration according to the manufacturer\u2019s instructions.",
      "dataProcessingProtocol": "Database Search MaxQuant and Andromeda search engine (v.1.5.1.8) were used to analyze the raw data of MS/MS (Cox and Mann, 2008;Cox et al., 2009). The tandem mass spectra collected were searched againsFusarium oxysporum database from UniProt. Mass errors of fragment ions and precursor were set as 0.02 Da and 10 ppm, respectively. Trypsin/P was specified as cleavage enzyme allowing up to 4 missing cleavage, 5 charges and 5 modifications per peptide. Carbamidomethylation on Cysteine was specified as fixed modification and acetylation on lysine was fixed as variable modification. The minimal peptide was set to seven, and the false discovery rate (FDR) threshold for modification sites and peptides were set as 1%. The Kac site localization probability of <0.75 was exclude (Zhou et al., 2016;Yang et al., 2018).",
      "projectTags": [],
      "keywords": [
        "Lc-ms/ms",
        "Lysine acetylation",
        "Fusarium oxysporum"
      ],
